She flipped to a blank page and wrote the date on it. Then, she wrote below the date: "5/11/648-12/13/648".
"Looking back on the past?" Avery asked, looking at the old notebook. Carly nodded. "Do you think they'll let you go out for Christmas? There are only a few days left until Christmas."
Carly tapped twice on the lantern, indicating "No." Just as Avery had expected. The Ice King never allowed Carly to go out, because in his eyes, Carly was "a flaw." Carly was born mute and was the only girl in the family; the other children were all boys.
Avery was also like that, in their unique way. When Avery came out as non-binary, the world seemed to change as well. As a punishment for their uniqueness, Avery was often left to work alone for most of the time.
They were also forced to be the princess's servant. But they didn't mind, because they had a friend.
“Your birthday is coming up soon, isn't it?” Avery asked, remembering that it would be Princess's birthday in a few days. Carly nodded, a hint of sadness flashing in her light blue eyes.
“Do you want to celebrate it?” Avery asked, recalling how Carly had answered this question last time.
Not at all. Carly tapped the table. Avery knew this was a hard topic for Carly to bring up. On this very day, she had been locked in this room, while her mother was executed. When it happened, Avery was still a baby, but TA remembered the anger of the servants and citizens at that time. TA had heard that Queen Elwen was a good queen and could even predict future events.
“So… what do you want to do?” Avery asked. Carly looked up at Avery with excitement. She handed Avery a piece of paper. However, when he looked down…
6-inch X 6-inch canvas
White, various shades of blue pigment
6 brushes of different sizes
Painting easel
“Are you trying to get me to bring these things for you?” Avery turned to the silent princess, who was constantly tapping and her ponytail swaying back and forth. “Is that right?” When she saw the usually quiet and reserved princess so enthusiastic about something, she couldn’t help but giggle. This was the first time she wanted something outside of her room, and it had nothing to do with books.
“Okay! See you later?” Avery said, standing up and walking through the messy papers and notebooks.
Kari nodded, continued to burrow deeper into the thick blanket, and reviewed her memories.
TA stepped out of the room, thinking that the princess finally wanted to try new things, and that TA was relieved to see her make requests beyond TA's capabilities (such as paint).
TA passed through the hall again, trying not to pay attention to the servants' whispered gossip.
"I heard she was possessed by Queen Elwin, so she always goes to that room."
"I heard she eats children in that room."
"She looks like a man, is that normal?"
TA couldn't stand hearing these words anymore, so had to cover their ears. TA went to the room of the royal painter, which was in the east wing, the second door on the left.
Avery arrived at that door, which was just as elaborately decorated as Carly's. The door had a white dragon painted on it, one of the six original dragons, said to have created the Frostland Kingdom. The painter loved history, so it was no wonder he painted the white dragon on the door.
TA opened the door, expecting everything to be as before. For example, there were paints everywhere, pencils and papers scattered all over the floor, and the easel covered every inch of the wall. However, the scene inside the room was completely different. The room was clean, with a red velvet background cloth and a chair. The chair was occupied by Prince Aquiro, who was painting a portrait.
"Ah, good morning, Avery! Want to see the portrait of your future king?" Aquiro asked, winking at Avery.
“Sorry, Your Highness,” said TA, beginning to search around for the things Princess Carly wanted. “I’m just here to get some art supplies.”
“Sweetheart, are you leaving already?” asked Aquiro. “But I still want to meet you!”
“I really don’t want to,” said Avery, finding the art supplies on the list and putting them into a box. “And also, I’m not a girl.”
The prince didn’t think so. “Oh, sweetheart, you know this is just a phase! It’ll be fine when you grow up!” He said vaguely.
“I have to go,” said TA, suddenly feeling very uncomfortable because the prince was still talking nonstop. TA recalled all the negative comments people had made about TA’s gender identity. I really want to get away from him.
“Are you leaving so soon?” The prince suddenly appeared at the door, ignoring the royal painter's shouts.
“This is not the behavior of a future king!” TA shouted fiercely.
“No one will know. People won't believe you, and if that painter still values his life, he wouldn't say such things.” The prince looked back at the painter and then leaned close to Avery. “What do you think about a date?” TA trembled with fear. Of course, TA had heard many threats before, but these threats were never from the prince, let alone the future king.
“Do you know what the word ‘no’ means?” TA shouted, pushing the crown prince away.
“No.” Aquiro laughed in response. The crown prince, who could get whatever he wanted, of course didn’t know what the word “no” meant.
Avery rolled his eyes. "Why so many people, and you just want to date me? How many admirers do you have? A hundred?"
He laughed and interrupted, "Actually, it's over five hundred." He shook his hair, swaying in the cold wind.
"See? Why me? I'm the curse of the palace." She hugged her arms.
"You're the most beautiful girl I've ever seen." Aquiro placed a finger on Avery's chin, forcing her to look up at him.
